  "prompt": "Why is Chicago called the \"City of Broad Shoulders\"?",
  "response": "Chicago is often referred to as the \"City of Broad Shoulders,\" a phrase attributed to the poet Carl Sandburg, who used it in his poem \"Chicago.\" The imagery of \"broad shoulders\" symbolizes strength, resilience, and the hardworking nature of the city's people. Sandburg's portrayal reflects the city's industrial roots and its role as a hub of commerce and labor during the early 20th century.\n\nThe phrase also captures the city's spirit and identity, emphasizing the determination and grit of its residents, who contributed to Chicago's growth and development as a major American metropolis. Overall, the nickname evokes both the physicality of the city\u2014evidenced by its towering skyscrapers and robust economy\u2014and the character of its inhabitants, known for their toughness and sense of community.",
